\begin_layout Enumerate
Q1: The Electric field in Coulomb’s and Gauss’ Law
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Why does Gauss’s law constitute a generalization of Coulomb’s law? What
 are the elements of Coulomb’s law, both fundamental and restrictive, that
 are still contained in the concept of electric field as defined by Gauss’
 law?
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Q2: Applications of Gauss’ law: Earnshaw’s theorem
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Use Gauss’ law to demonstrate that a positive charge placed at the center
 of an equilateral triangle with equal negative charges –q at each summit
 of the triangle will not be in a stable equilibrium.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Use vector calculus to demonstrate that a generic constant electric dipole
 𝑝⃗ cannot be in a stable equilibrium in a generic electrostatic field 𝐸$⃗
 .
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
[Hint: Stable equilibrium required 𝛻$⃗ ∙ 𝐹⃗ < 0.
 This can also be expressed in terms of the potential energy U.
 For an electric dipole, 𝑈 = −𝑝⃗ ∙ 𝐸$⃗ ] 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
